>Someone with psychiatric problems may expereience what s=
ounds like a Kundalini rise, but it may or may not be one.
>=C2=A0
>It must=
 be conceded though that Kundalini spontaneously rising through various nad=
is without one having gone through proper preparation in this life (i.e. fi=
ne-tuning of one's attitude and development of detachment) CAN create havoc=
!
>=C2=A0
>One may wonder how Kundalini may spontaneously rise in a layman =
with no sadhana, while many serious sadhakas may not experience it.
>=C2=A0=

>Firstly, Kundalini rise is NOT an achievement. It is just A SMALL STEP in=
 overcoming one's current limited identity.
>=C2=A0
>Let me give an analogy=
. One wanting to move from one's small dilapidated house (this body-mind co=
mplex) to a huge palace (realized Self) may first construct the palace over=
 time and move into it when it is COMPLETE. Alternately, if one occasionall=
y goes and stays in the palace still under construction (analogy for out of=
 body experiences due to Kundalini rise), is it an achievement? In fact, it=
 comes with risks. The former approach is safer and one loses nothing in it=
. Similarly, one can progress towards complete Self-realization without any=
 out of body experiences. These are not my word's, but Maharshi Vasishtha's=
 words to Lord Rama.
>=C2=A0
>Secondly, one does not get something without =
wanting it and putting sufficient effort towards it. One may have deeply de=
sired a Kundalini rise in a previous life and may have put enough effort. A=
s a result, one may be getting it now. But one may be unprepared (and ironi=
cally may not even want it!) when it comes in this life.
>=C2=A0
>As you do=
 sadhana, try not to fancy too many specific desires. Nature has a delay me=
chanism in granting your desires (because of constraints on what Nature can=
 give you right now, arising from YOUR OWN previous actions). So Nature som=
etimes gives you what you want LATE, when you no longer want it or want som=
ething else. For example, one may pray for great wealth one's whole life an=
d be born as a rich but very sick man in next life. One may not enjoy that =
wealth and pray whole life for health. In the life after that, one may be v=
ery healthy, but not have any knowledge or money. In another case, one may =
deeply desire to act in a famous film. One may be reborn as a tiger or a do=
g and act in a famous film, but not really enjoy that experience. Basically=
, people keep going in circles through various lives, always "seeking" some=
thing they are "missing".
>=C2=A0
>Anyway, coming back to Kundalini, if one=
 deeply desires an out of body experience given by a rising Kundalini and o=
ne's previous karmas constrain one from having it in THIS life, one may be =
born in next life with this specific desire destined to fructify (if there =
is enough karmik force behind it).
>=C2=A0
