<DIV>Dear all, Just wanted to warn people of =
kundalini syndrome based on my recent experience of a patient of mine. I am=
 doing a psychiatry job at present, and have been involved in the care of s=
omeone who seems to think she has had a spontaneous awakening of their kund=
alini since childhood. This has involved out-of-body experiences and surges=
 of energy in the body. She is not of Indian origin and had never heard of =
kundalini until her symptoms started and she searched for an explanation. W=
e have not been able to find anything physically wrong with her (all tests =
normal)- so it might be that this is due to deranged kundalini. Many people=
 we call mentally ill describe themselves as having a spiritual crisis, or =
unwanted spontaneous kundalini awakening- this has triggered interest and r=
esearch into this topic in mainstream psychiatry. Unfortunately these patie=
nts are not well-understood by western medicine, and as we have no treatmen=
ts for deranged
 kundalini, we struggle to help them. Many yogis try to for=
cibly waken the kundalini. My experience with this lady confirmed my feelin=
g that kundalini should not be forcibly wakened. This woman wants to kill h=
erself at times because the suffering from the deranged energy is so bad. S=
he feels it will consume her, and it is something she cannot escape from. I=
 wondered what solution there could be to her problem. The logical one was =
to pray to the Divine Mother, who manifests as the kundalini to relieve the=
 suffering of this woman- and either cure her, or give her the strength to =
bear this. May I request that the good samaritans among you pray for her, a=
nd for others like her (whom we may not know of)- their suffering really is=
 pitiable. And let us be careful in our sadhana so as not to end up in this=
 situation ourselves. Perhaps this is why the bhakti marga is the safest. I=
t is perhaps safest to say "let me be your instrument" and leave the kundal=
ini
